{"id":"2006.07082","submitter":"Snehal M. Shekatkar Dr.","authors":"Madhusudan Ingale, Snehal M. Shekatkar","title":"Resource dependency and survivability in complex networks","comments":"8 pages, 9 figures. Code is freely available at\n  https://gitlab.com/snehalshekatkar/dependency-networks","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 102, 062304 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.102.062304","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph cs.SI nlin.AO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Components in many real-world complex systems depend on each other for the\nresources required for survival, and may die of a shortage. These patterns of\ndependencies often take the form of a complex network whose structure\npotentially affects how the resources produced in the system are efficiently\nshared among its components, which in turn decides a network's survivability.\nHere we present a simple threshold model that provides insight into this\nrelationship between the network structure and survivability. We show that, as\na combined effect of local sharing and finite lifetime of resources, many\ncomponents in a complex system may die of lack of resources even when\nsufficient amount is available in the system. We also obtain a surprising\nresult that although the scale-free networks exhibit a significantly higher\nsurvivability compared to their homogeneous counterparts, a vertex in the later\nsurvives longer on average. Finally, we demonstrate that the system's\nsurvivability can be substantially improved by changing the way vertices\ndistribute resources among the neighbours. Our work is a step towards\nunderstanding the relationship between intricate resource dependencies present\nin many real-world complex systems and their survivability.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 12 Jun 2020 11:09:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Jun 2020 07:14:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 11 Dec 2020 11:52:09 GMT"},{"version":"v4","c